==Old English==
===Etymology===
From German ''*wurða-'', from Indo-European ''*werdho-'' ‘word’, from ''*wer-'' ‘speak’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''word'', Old Saxon ''word'' (Dutch [[woord]]), Old High German [[wort]] (German [[Wort]]), Old Norse [[orð]] (Swedish [[ord]]), Gothic [[𐍅𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌳]].  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[verbum]], Lithuanian [[vardas]], and more distantly of Greek [[εἴρω]] ‘I say’, Old Slavic ''rotiti sę'' ‘swear’ (Russian [[ротиться]] ‘vow’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /woɹd/

===Noun===
'''word''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''word''')
# a [[word]]
# [[speech]], an [[utterance]], a [[statement]]
# [[news]], [[information]], a [[rumour]]
# a [[command]] or [[request]]

